<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-194-342  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 194 342.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 17 1989 v23 n16 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GAO audit can't justify Ada adoption. (General Accounting Office)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Betts, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A GAO audit of the Department of Defense's Ada software initiativeshows that there is still no evidence that the use of Ada ishelping to control the DOD's runaway software development andmaintenance costs.andP;  The DOD adopted Ada nine years ago as aportable and reliable language capable of being easily maintainedand reused.andP;  At the time, the agency was faced with softwaredevelopment costs of $3 billion a year and 300 differentprogramming languages or versions of languages.andP;  The GAO's reviewof 100 Ada projects shows that 77 involve the development ofcomputer applications for operational systems.andP;  The audit alsodetermined: that the availability of Ada compilers is no longer aproblem for most DOD applications, that DOD validation ofcompilers ensures that they conform to the language standard, andthat Ada is being used successfully in some real-timeapplications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ADAAuditing of Computer SystemsCritiqueCost of ProgrammingCost Benefit AnalysisMilitary.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>